\doTocEntry\toclot{1}{\csname a:TocLink\endcsname{8}{x8-560011}{}{\ignorespaces DIII-D cyclone base case parameters{\cite  {Dimits2000}}{\cite  {gorler2016}} where $R_0$ is the major radius of the magnetic axis, $a$ is the minor radius of the last-closed-flux-surface, $q_0$ is the value of safety factor at $r = r_0 = 0.5 a$, $\hat  {s}_0$ is the value of the magnetic shear $\hat  {s} = r q^{- 1} d q / d r$ at $r = r_0$. $B_{\ensuremath  {\operatorname  {axis}}}$ is the magnetic field strength at the magnetic axis. The toroidal field function $g (r) = B_{\phi } R$ is assumed to be a constant independent of $r$, i.e., $g = B_{\ensuremath  {\operatorname  {axis}}} R_0$. $T_{i 0}$ is the ion temperature at $r = r_0$. Assume Deuterium plasma, then $R_0 / \rho _i = 500$ and $a / \rho _i = 180$. where $\rho _i = \sqrt  {T_{i 0} / m_i} / \Omega _i$ is the thermal ion gyro-radius, $\Omega _i = B_{\ensuremath  {\operatorname  {axis}}} q_i / m_i$ is the ion cyclotron angular frequency at the magnetic axis.}}{table}\relax 
\doTocEntry\toclof{3}{\csname a:TocLink\endcsname{8}{x8-560073}{}{\ignorespaces Radial profiles of safety factor, temperature, and density of the above DIII-D cyclone test case. The dashed lines indicate the radial simulation box $0.3 \leqslant r / a \leqslant 0.7$.}}{figure}\relax 
